entry.title: [base] Prevent post-shutdown check from CONTINUE_ON_SHUTDOWN scope.
entry.content:
A CONTINUE_ON_SHUTDOWN task may still be running after the ThreadPool

has been shutdown. A race where it posts back to a BLOCK_SHUTDOWN

sequence is a coincidence and cannot be considered part of a series of

shutdown blocking work, it is therefore okay to fizzle the check in

that case.



New PostAfterShutdownFromContinueOnShutdown test fails, as desired,

without accompanying task_tracker.cc change.

entry.title: [ios] Track duration of the password save/update infobar
entry.content:
This CL adds the PasswordManager.iOS.InfoBar.{Type}Duration.{Moment}

metric which is summarized as follow:

"""

Records the duration of the password save/update infobar that is

presented after using new credentials. Recorded when the

password infobar banner is dismissed.



Token key "Type":

- variant "Save": the save infobar

- variant "Update": the update infobar



Token key "Moment":

- variant "All": all moments

- variant "OnDeletion": when deleting the infobar

- variant "OnDismiss: when dismissing the infobar

"""



This CL has also other effects:

* Record metrics as soon as the infobar is dismissed instead of

waiting until deletion. This should be no op as the infobar can

only be presented once during the lifetime of the delegate, hence

there shouldn't be a difference in the metrics when recording right

after dismissal VS on delegate deletion. This has the advantage of

speeding up the recording of infobar metrics on dismiss.

entry.title: Make legacy colors store [0,255] internally
entry.content:
See discussion here: https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/9759

This CL fixes WPTs that are being were added here:

https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/43931/files



We were previously normalizing legacy srgb colors so that they could

be treated interchangeably with non-legacy srgb colors. Unfortunately

this breaks math for relative colors, for example:



rgb(from red calc(r - 127) g b)



Should result in a half red, not black.



The clearest way to fix this is simply to store legacy srgb colors in

the [0,255] range, so that we're not faking it on serialization

either. This of course makes conversions more complex as we have to

tread SRGBLegacy and SRGB as different color spaces, though they are

converted between one another by a simple multiplication or division

by 255.



Also in this CL:

- Renamed ClampInt to ClampInt255, since that's what it does.

- Added a SerializeInternal() function to blink::Color that both CSS,

Legacy and Canvas serializers all use. It's useful for debugging since

it does not do things like converting hsl/hwb to srgb.

- Removed color-valid-relative-color.html from failure expectations,

so now we have an expectations file.



The six new failures in color-computed-relative-color are due to bad

tests that assume this mapping specifically does not happen.



Of the 42 failures in color-valid-relative-color, 36 are old and were

being suppressed by testExpectations. The 6 new ones are the same as

for the computed file.

entry.title: Reland "Don't emit shadow predictions for all pairs of PatternSources"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 11d8e0bd69de05415aaf097be19934ec3f3c08f0



The original CL broke some UKM metric tests on Chrome-branded builds.

This wasn't caught by the CQ, since it only contains non Chrome-branded

builds.

This is fixed by changing the expectations accordingly (i.e. don't

expect type predictions for next-gen patterns when the default patterns

are active).



Original change's description:

> Don't emit shadow predictions for all pairs of PatternSources

>

> Currently, on Chrome-branded builds with pattern provider enabled,

> predictions for the default, experimental and next-gen set are computed.

> Shadow predictions for all pairs are emitted.

>

> Given that every new regex will need to make it through next-gen ->

> experimental -> default, comparing next-gen with default doesn't make

> much sense. This CL removes this shadow prediction histogram.

>

> This enables a key simplification: Instead of computing default,

> experimental and next-gen predictions for every form, it suffices to

> compute only two of them; either default and experimental or

> experimental and next-gen, depending on whether default or

> experimental is the active source*.

> This reduces the pattern provider overhead from 3x to 2x.

>

> (The actual logic is slightly more complicated, since ML predictions

> exist as well: When ML is active, shadow predictions against the

> pattern source that would otherwise be active are computed. When ML is

> enabled as an inactive prediction source, shadow predictions for it

> are computed in addition to the PatternProvider shadow predictions)

>

> OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Autofill.ShadowPredictions.NextGenToDefault]=See CL

> description

>

> * As per design doc, only default (99% of users) and experimental

> patterns (1% of users) will be active in practice.

> https://docs.google.com/document/d/12Fr4wWozA3Rd62D9Imf_86gQVb3BEI8_NCDpNsrkULw/edit?tab=t.0

copies of //net:



- WaitForPrefLoad accessed via libcronet.*.so

- FlushWritePropertiesForTesting accessed via libcronet_tests.so



The `SequenceChecker` inside ` prefs_update_timer_` observed a

different `base::internal::SequenceToken` in each case (there is a

different instance of `current_sequence_token` in shared library).

This resulted in a DCHECK failure.



The solution is to use a single copy of //net to access a given

`net::HttpServerProperties` object.



Low-Coverage-Reason: COVERAGE_UNDERREPORTED CronetContext::FlushWritePropertiesForTesting is a test-only function which is definitely invoked in tests, despite code-coverage detecting that it isn't covered by tests.

entry.title: [DBSC] Fix bug in overriding a session
entry.content:
Gaia is currently using a constant session id. The current

implementation of `RegisterNewBoundSession`:

- Saves the new session params

- If there is an existing session it clears it from storage.

- If session id and storage are the same, this will also clear the new

session.



In practice, this can happen if the user is redirected to sign in and a

new session is started. With Gaia using the same session id, this will

result in the bound session being terminated on next startup (session

cleared from storage) and the user signed out.

entry.title: display::DisplaySnapshot: Separate out ColorInfo
entry.content:
The display::DisplaySnapshot::color_space property does many things

which need to be separated out. This is towards removing this

property and replacing it with several separate properties.



At present, display::DisplaySnapshot::color_space provides the one

and only color space that may be used for DRM planes. We wish to allow

DRM planes to have different color spaces, and use the display hardware

to perform color conversion.



To this end, add a separate display::DisplaySnapshot::ColorInfo

structure that lists all of the color management properties of

the display controller. From this, the browser will choose what

color space to use for the DRM planes.



Future patches will:

- remove the gfx::ColorSpace from display::DisplaySnapshot::ColorInfo

- add sufficient information to gfx::HDRStaticMetadata to determine

if HDR10 is available

- add to display::DisplaySnapshot::ColorInfo information about a

functional degamma-ctm-gamma pipeline is present

- add to display::DisplaySnapshot::ColorInfo information about if

per-plane CTM is available (in the distant future)

entry.title: Revert "Don't emit shadow predictions for all pairs of PatternSources"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 11d8e0bd69de05415aaf097be19934ec3f3c08f0.



Reason for revert: suspect for breaking ChromeOS:

https://ci.chromium.org/p/chrome/builders/ci/linux-chromeos-chrome/b8758749625595788721



Original change's description:

> Don't emit shadow predictions for all pairs of PatternSources

>

> Currently, on Chrome-branded builds with pattern provider enabled,

> predictions for the default, experimental and next-gen set are computed.

> Shadow predictions for all pairs are emitted.

>

> Given that every new regex will need to make it through next-gen ->

> experimental -> default, comparing next-gen with default doesn't make

> much sense. This CL removes this shadow prediction histogram.

>

> This enables a key simplification: Instead of computing default,

> experimental and next-gen predictions for every form, it suffices to

> compute only two of them; either default and experimental or

> experimental and next-gen, depending on whether default or

> experimental is the active source*.

> This reduces the pattern provider overhead from 3x to 2x.

>

> (The actual logic is slightly more complicated, since ML predictions

> exist as well: When ML is active, shadow predictions against the

> pattern source that would otherwise be active are computed. When ML is

> enabled as an inactive prediction source, shadow predictions for it

> are computed in addition to the PatternProvider shadow predictions)

>

> OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Autofill.ShadowPredictions.NextGenToDefault]=See CL

> description

>

> * As per design doc, only default (99% of users) and experimental

> patterns (1% of users) will be active in practice.

entry.content:
When entering tabs search, I tried with Compositional Layout to keep the

Inactive Tabs button visible under the shadow, as it provided a nicer

transition from the grid itself. But since headers are not easily

recreated with Diffable Data Source (we'd have to create a new section

new section), this leads to some cases where the header was wrong.

currently shipping codepath).

to land, remove the Flow Layout codepath, and move the Inactive Tabs

entry.title: [Passwords] Fix showing suggestions on fields with manual generation
entry.content:
When a password field is focused, AutofillAgent queries

PasswordGenerationAgent for suggestions, and if no generation is

required, it queries PasswordAutofillAgent.

PasswordGenerationAgent::ShowPasswordGenerationSuggestions should

return true only when generation suggestions are offered.

But in case when generation is triggered manually, and then the

value is erased by the user, the method keeps returning true, even

though the generation suggestions are not shown anymore.



Fixing the bug by allowing the method to return false, then

AutofillAgent is able to query PasswordAutofillAgent.

entry.title: Replace EmbeddedTestServer with NativeTestServer
entry.content:
* Currently, there are four different test servers being used for Cronet testing,

which can be listed as follow:

1. QuicTestServer: serves QUIC requests only.

2. Http2TestServer: serves HTTP2 requests and uses netty.

3. NativeTestServer: serves HTTP1 requests and uses net:test_server

4. EmbeddedTestServer: serves HTTP1 requests and uses net:test_server



The goal here is to remove EmbeddedTestServer from our dependencies

and replace it usages with NativeTestServer, the difference between those

is that EmbeddedTestServer is an out-of-process test server while

NativeTestServer is an in-process test server. there is no behavioral differences

at all.



* I implemented some missing methods that were needed in the NativeTestServer

JNI layer to allow enabling SSL, I have not complete and thorough testing to

see if SSL will work in every case but this seems enough to pass the tests that

we bundle.



* NativeTestServer is much easier to maintain as it exists in-process and makes our

test configuration simpler which translate to easier test configuration in AOSP aswell. However,

Choosing NativeTestServer or EmbeddedTestServer is a hard decision, so I thought of simply removing

EmbeddedTestServer for now and let the test of time determine if that was a good enough decision or not.



----- Prior History Of NativeTestServer ------



Initially, it was called UploadTestServer (https://codereview.chromium.org/640593004) and it

was created when net:embedded_server already existed. It added additional functionalities above

what already existed (eg: https://codereview.chromium.org/723783002, https://codereview.chromium.org/773183003/patch/20001/30002, https://codereview.chromium.org/784583003).



At that time (https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/tags/42.0.2273.0:net/android/BUILD.gn;bpv=0), the EmbeddedTestServer only

existed as a native implementation, there was no JNI support and Cronet team had to implement their own NativeTestServer, after some time, net team implemented

an identical implementation which is now known as "EmbeddedTestServer".

entry.title: Don't emit shadow predictions for all pairs of PatternSources
entry.content:
Currently, on Chrome-branded builds with pattern provider enabled,

predictions for the default, experimental and next-gen set are computed.

Shadow predictions for all pairs are emitted.



Given that every new regex will need to make it through next-gen ->

experimental -> default, comparing next-gen with default doesn't make

much sense. This CL removes this shadow prediction histogram.



This enables a key simplification: Instead of computing default,

experimental and next-gen predictions for every form, it suffices to

compute only two of them; either default and experimental or

experimental and next-gen, depending on whether default or

experimental is the active source*.

This reduces the pattern provider overhead from 3x to 2x.



(The actual logic is slightly more complicated, since ML predictions

exist as well: When ML is active, shadow predictions against the

pattern source that would otherwise be active are computed. When ML is

enabled as an inactive prediction source, shadow predictions for it

are computed in addition to the PatternProvider shadow predictions)



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Autofill.ShadowPredictions.NextGenToDefault]=See CL

description



* As per design doc, only default (99% of users) and experimental

patterns (1% of users) will be active in practice.

https://docs.google.com/document/d/12Fr4wWozA3Rd62D9Imf_86gQVb3BEI8_NCDpNsrkULw/edit?tab=t.0
